{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487306","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487306"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"315"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/315"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.13,0.7,0.01,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50029"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"315","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/315"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"315"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35280"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"33"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1372"},{"type":"tags","id":"1635"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11403"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12388"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13818"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42055"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50029"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after sustaining a stab wound to the chest during an altercation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears fully alert and oriented, able to recall all events surrounding the injury. His breathing is laboured with a respiratory rate of 28/min. His pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/60 mmHg, temperature 37.3\u00b0C and SpO2 96% on room air. Examination of his chest reveals a 3 cm laceration in the left mid-axillary line in the fifth intercostal space, with underlying muscle visible. There is reduced air entry and dullness to percussion on the left side of the chest. He has no other injuries. An intravenous catheter is inserted and fluid resuscitation is commenced.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest","Thoracotomy","Intercostal drain","Sternotomy","Commence intermittent positive pressure ventilation"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of haemodynamic instability suggestive of hypovolaemia due to blood loss from the chest laceration. His laboured breathing, reduced air entry, and dullness to percussion on the left chest are consistent with lung collapse/compression and fluid collection, indicating an open pneumothorax and haemothorax. The priority is to replace the lost blood volume and drain the chest to facilitate lung re-expansion. Intravenous isotonic saline should be rapidly infused while a prompt \u003Cstrong\u003Eintercostal drain\u003C/strong\u003E is inserted to allow egress of accumulated blood and air from the pleural space. The stab wound must then be covered with a firm dressing to prevent further air entry into the chest.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest\u003C/strong\u003E would provide detailed imaging of the thoracic injuries but is not the immediate priority in an unstable patient with a clear indication for chest drainage. Delaying definitive management for imaging could lead to further deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ethoracotomy\u003C/strong\u003E may become necessary if initial measures fail to control the situation, particularly in cases of ongoing haemorrhage. However, it is a more invasive procedure and is not the first-line management in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Esternotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is a surgical procedure that involves dividing the sternum to access the heart and great vessels. It is typically used for cardiac surgery or to access mediastinal structures. In this case of a lateral chest wound, a sternotomy would be overly invasive and inappropriate as an initial management step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntermittent positive pressure ventilation\u003C/strong\u003E delivered non-invasively could theoretically tamponade some bleeding and assist ventilation. However, it does not address the underlying haemothorax, and delaying definitive drainage is potentially hazardous. Positive pressure may also worsen the pneumothorax if applied before chest decompression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing this patient is to promptly address the immediate life-threatening conditions - in this case, the haemothorax and potential pneumothorax - before proceeding with further investigations or more invasive interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In cases of chest trauma, an intercostal drain will help decompress any pneumothorax and allow removal of blood, the latter to help with assessment of fluid loss.","Immediate chest decompression takes priority over imaging in unstable patients with clear signs of haemothorax or pneumothorax."],"references":["Dennis BM. Bellister SA, Guillamondegui OD. Thoracic Trauma. Surg Clin N Am 2017; 97:1047-64. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28958357/","Zeiler J, Idell S, Norwood S, Cook A. Hemothorax: A Review of the Literature. Clin Pulm Med. 2020;27(1):1-12. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33437141/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35280"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"315"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35280","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35280"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-05T21:26:43+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T21:30:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"315"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50029"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"33","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/33"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiothoracic Surgery","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt"